properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT KIALLA WEST

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT STRATHBOGIE TUESDAY EVENING

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT EUROA DURING OVERNIGHT TUESDAY

Minor flooding may develop at Euroa during overnight Tuesday. Moderate flooding is occurring at Kialla West with further rises possible.

Since 9:00am Tuesday, rainfall totals of up to 25mm have been observed across the Seven and Castle Creeks catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Tuesday into Wednesday.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa

Moderate flooding is occurring along the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.

The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is currently at 5.17 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is likely to remain above the moderate flood level (5.00m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. Further rises are possible as upstream floodwaters arrive.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions.
What you should do:

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
Returning home:
  •  Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician. For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.   A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.  
Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 26/10/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     
  • Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away including canned and packaged foods.   
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Recovery: 
  •  Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance Call 000 If your home is about to flood Call VICSES on 132 500
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.webBody:
The Emergency Warning to Evacuate, following flooding at Echuca south of Ogilvie Avenue has been lifted and it is Safe to Return.

Major flooding occurring at Echuca and Moama is peaking around the current level during Tuesday, higher than the 1975 and 1993 floods. 
  • The Murray River at Echuca at 5pm Tuesday 25 October measured 94.93 metres AHD. 
  • An Emergency Warning - Evacuate Immediately remains in place for parts of Echuca and Echuca Village.
  • Dangerous hazards including floodwater, mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees may still be present. 
  • If your buildings have been impacted by flood waters you should have your property inspected by a registered electrician. Visit the Energy Safe Victoria site for more: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/energy-safety-during-floods/
  • For more information on any assistance you need, visit emergency.vic.gov.au/relief/#relief_assistance
It is now safe to return the evacuated area to assess impacts as the threat is reduced. Be aware of any hazards that may still exist in the warning area. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded.
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 
For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area:
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
  • River heights in parts of Echuca and Echuca Village are likely to remain high for days.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning issued for this area unless the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Recreational/commercial use of the Murray River
For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: The NSW State Emergency Service have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumwal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/

Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease. 
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods
If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.

This updated Emergency Warning is being issued for Kerang.

  • An evacuation warning remains current and it is still not safe to return.
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is currently at 77.84m Australian Height Datum (AHD) and steady, with major flooding. The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is likely to remain around the major flood level (77.80m) during Tuesday.
  • Dangerous flood water is still significantly impacting Kerang and surrounding areas, continue to avoid flood-affected areas.
  • Emergency services and Gannawarra Shire Council are working together to assess levee integrity, road safety and identify any impacts to essential services.
  • Although the river has peaked, with some levees still overtopped in sections, many areas are still experiencing significant flooding and emergency services continue efforts towards sandbagging and asset protection.

It is not safe for people to return to Kerang. If you have not evacuated, avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
If you have not already evacuated:
  • Stay where you are and be aware of changing conditions. If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story.
  • Be aware that you may still become isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time.
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance.
If you have already evacuated:
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued.
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
This evacuation warning will remain in place until emergency services have confirmed that the threat to Kerang has reduced, and it is safe to return.
Impacts in your area:
  • The Kerang-Quambatook Road is closed.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is closed east of Kerang between Sleepy Lane and Phillips Road.
  • The Old Echuca Road is closed between Durham Ox and Kerang.
  • The Loddon Valley Highway is closed south of Kerang.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is closed north of Kerang.
  • Be aware that snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/campaigns/beat-the-bite

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

MODERATE FLOODING MAY DEVELOP AT SHEPPARTON OVERNIGHT TUESDAY INTO WEDNESDAY

MODERATE FLOODING HAS EASED AT SEYMOUR

RAPID RISES IN TRIBUTARIES ARE POSSIBLE OVERNIGHT TUESDAY INTO WEDNESDAY

Moderate flooding has eased easing along the Goulburn River at Seymour. Minor flooding is continuing at Murchison. Moderate flooding may develop at Shepparton overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. Moderate flooding is continuing at McCoys Bridge. Rapid rises in tributaries are possible overnight Tuesday into Wednesday in response to the thunderstorms. 

Since 9:00 am Tuesday, rainfall totals of up to 50 mm due to thunderstorms have been recorded in the Goulburn River catchment.  Further rainfall and thunderstorms are forecast overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton

  • Moderate flooding may occur along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 9.91 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at Murchison is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.00 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. 
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 10.65 metres and rising slowly, with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at Shepparton may reach the moderate flood level (10.70 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.
This is an update, replacing the Advice message issued at 12.01 PM, 25/10/2022.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Returning home 
  •  Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician. For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/

Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Murchison Bridge is open for LIGHT traffic only-The Murchison Bridge on High Road linking Murchison and Murchison East is now closed to heavy transport traffic and farm machinery until the structural integrity of the bridge is assessed.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 26/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Recovery:
  •  Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   
  • Call 1800 560 760 If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance Call 000 If your home is about to flood Call VICSES on 132 500.

Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     
  • Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away including canned and packaged foods.   
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.

Major flooding is easing slowly along the Loddon River at Kerang. Moderate flooding is easing at Appin South.

Kerang could become isolated overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. Road closures on the Benjeroop-Lake Charm Road are likely. The Benjeroop-Tresco Road has been closed due to floodwater.

If you are located in Kerang, leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous. If you choose to stay overnight, be aware that you may be isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time.

  • The Loddon River at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir is currently at 6.32m and rising, with moderate flooding.
  • The Loddon River at Appin South is currently at 3.21m and falling, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.10m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is currently at 77.81m Australian Height Datum (AHD) and easing slowly, with major flooding. The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is likely to remain around the major flood level (77.80m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.
Act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground.
What you should do: 
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesnt take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
Impacts in your area: 
  • A number of local and arterial roads are closed due to floodwater. For more information on road closures go to https://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au
  • Some areas are likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Be aware that snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/campaigns/beat-the-bite

  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.   
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.  
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.

RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM TUESDAY.

Showers and thunderstorms are possible across most of the state during Tuesday, more likely on and north of the divide, contracting to central and eastern districts during Wednesday and Thursday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, many of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Renewed areas of minor to moderate flooding are possible from Tuesday in the flood watch area.

In locations where thunderstorms develop, particularly in west and south Gippsland, localised flooding due to heavy rainfall is possible.

The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

Macalister River
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 26/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for parts of Echuca and Echuca Village. 
If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

Major flooding occurring at Echuca and Moama is peaking around the current level during Tuesday, higher than the 1975 and 1993 floods.

Floodwaters from the Campaspe and Goulburn Rivers combined with flows down the Murray River have caused major flooding at Echuca and Moama. River levels at Echuca Wharf have exceeded the October 1993 (94.77 m AHD) and November 1975 (94.80 m AHD) floods, and currently peaking slightly below 95.00 metres AHD, with major flooding.

MURRAY RIVER
  • Major flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Echuca, Moama, Torrumbarry, Barham.
  • The Murray River at Echuca is currently around 94.94 metres AHD, with major flooding. The Murray River at Echuca may remain around 94.90 metres during Tuesday into Wednesday with major flooding.
CAMPASPE RIVER
  • Moderate flooding is continuing along the Campaspe River at Echuca.
  • The river level along the Campaspe River at Echuca at 3pm Tuesday 25 October measured 94.67 m AHD and steady, with moderate flooding. 
  • The river is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (94.40 m AHD) for the remainder of Tuesday and into Wednesday. 
  • Renewed rises are occurring due to flood waters backing up from the Murray River and are expected to continue in the coming days.
For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: The NSW State Emergency Service have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
If you are located in the warning areas, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately. If you do not relocate now you may become isolated for a number of days. If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. The EVACUATION ROUTE is currently open but may not stay that way.

The Echuca Emergency Relief Centre (Echuca South Basketball Stadium located at 244 High street, Echuca) can be accessed by people if required.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • Travel to family and friends outside of the impacted area.
  • Travel direct to Bendigo Relief Centre, Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Road Bendigo.
  • The Echuca Emergency Relief Centre (Echuca South Basketball Stadium .located at 244 High Street, Echuca) can be accessed by people if required.
  • For evacuation route follow this link: Evacuation Route
If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
If you stay:  
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you.
  • Flood water is impacting sewerage systems in Echuca. Residents should limit water usage where possible-this will reduce the volume being sent to sewerage while flood levels are high.
  • Most levees are not designed for the level of flooding we are currently experiencing, so there are risks of overtopping and potential for breach or failure.
  • We urge the community to avoid being on or near the levee in Echuca township to reduce the risk of erosion and/or damage to the levee.
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Echuca village residents, if you do not relocate now you could become isolated for 10-15 days.
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate, is dangerous and may put your life at risk. 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Areas near the affected location may lose services including power, water, sewerage and phone coverage due to flooding.
  • Some residents may notice their toilets arent flushing or sinks arent draining as normal. Please consider minimising water use, including the use of washing machines and dishwashers, and limit baths and showers. This will to reduce the volume of water being sent to sewer while flood levels are high. It is recommended that where possible, 72 hours be retained for consumption if required.
  • Snakes can lose their home during a flood. As a result, they may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes. For more information, check the Better Health Website.
  • For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: NSW State Emergency Services have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
Mosquito Alert 
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease. 
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 26/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria. 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Flood Watch is being issued for the King Parrot Creek.

RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING ARE POSSIBLE FROM TUESDAY

Showers and thunderstorms may occur across most of the state during Tuesday, more likely on and north of the divide, contracting to central and eastern districts during Wednesday and Thursday.

A low pressure system and trough will cross Victoria over the next few days bringing widespread rainfall over the flood watch area. Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, many of which are experiencing ongoing flooding.

Renewed river rises are not expected to increase the currently forecast major flood peaks along the Murray River.

In locations where thunderstorms develop, particularly in the catchment, localised flooding is possible due to heavy rainfall.

This Advice replaces the Flood Watch issued at 4.21 PM 24/10/2022.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. 

Never Enter Floodwater.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees. 
What you should do:

  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 26/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Wharparilla area.. 

Flooding has impacted residents in the area of Glyn Road, Wharparilla. 

Flooding is expected to peak Thursday or Friday of this week.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted in or around Glyn Road Wharparilla.
  • Roads around the Glyn Road Wharparilla area may be be impacted.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT DOWNSTREAM BASIN CREEK.

MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT DOWNSTREAM BASIN CREEK FROM WEDNESDAY AFTERNOON AND AT JARRAHMOND OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY.

Overnight rainfall has caused river rises along the Bombala and Snowy rivers. Moderate flooding is easing at Bombala. Renewed river rises are occurring along the Snowy River and moderate flooding is likely at McKillops Bridge from Wednesday morning. Major flooding is possible along the Snowy River downstream ofMcKillops Bridge from Wednesday afternoon.

In the 24 hours to 5:00 pm Tuesday, rainfall totals up to 50 mm were observed across the Snowy River catchment. Thunderstorms and further rainfall are possible for the remainder of Tuesday and into Wednesday. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge:

Major flooding may occur along the Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge.

The Snowy River D/S Basin Ck is currently at 3.67 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Snowy River D/S Basin Ck is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (5.50 m) early Wednesday afternoon. The river level may reach the major flood level (6.60 m) Wednesday afternoon.

The Snowy River at Jarrahmond is currently at 3.90 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Snowy River at Jarrahmond is expected to exceed the minor flood level (4.10 m) Wednesday morning. The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (6.20 m) Wednesday night and may reach the major flood level (7.40 m) overnight Wednesday into Thursday.

The Snowy River at Orbost is currently at 4.20 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Snowy River at Orbost is expected to exceed the minor flood level (4.20 m) Wednesday afternoon. The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (6.00 m) overnight Wednesday into Thursday. Further rises are possible
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding. 


What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  •  Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  •  Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • Widespread flooding of the area.
  • Some areas will be likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
Major Level:
Several key roads may be cut by floodwaters affecting transport between neighbouring communities. These include Marlo Rd (under the Princes Hwy bridge and in several other locations between Orbost and Marlo), Bete Bolong Rd and Buchan-Orbost Rd (running parallel to the Snowy River from Orbost to Jarrahmond; lower Lochiel and Nicholson St (Orbost), and Lochend Rd (running parallel to Snowy River toward Corringle).

Moderate Level:

Lynn's and Gilbert's Gulches will have over topped, beginning to fill the floodplain and isolating properties. Snowy River floodwaters over Marlo Rd at Gilberts Gulch now connect with floodwaters backed up from the Brodribb River and Lake Curlip estuary. Main traffic routes may be affected: floodwaters may now be crossing sections of Bouchers Lane, Buchan-Orbost Rd, Huxters Rd, Marlo Rd and Nixons Rd. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. 
Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease. 
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods

If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.

  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  • Snakes can lose their home during a flood. As a result, they may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings. This Advice message is being issued for Lakes Entrance.

  • Due to a whale carcass at the beach there could be an increase in shark activity.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • The carcass was originally located in Marlo, but as of 21/10/2022, it has broken up and spread out along the coast between Lake Tyers Beach and Lakes Entrance.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Snowy River to McKillops Bridge.

MODERATE FLOODING LIKELY AT MCKILLOPS BRIDGE FROM WEDNESDAY MORNING AND AT ORBOST FROM OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY.

Overnight rainfall has caused river rises along the Bombala and Snowy rivers. Moderate flooding is easing at Bombala. Renewed river rises are occurring along the Snowy River and moderate flooding is likely at McKillops Bridge from Wednesday morning. 

In the 24 hours to 5:00 pm Tuesday, rainfall totals up to 50 mm were observed across the Snowy River catchment. Thunderstorms and further rainfall are possible for the remainder of Tuesday and into Wednesday. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Bombala River:

Moderate flooding is easing along the Bombala River.

The Bombala River at Bombala peaked at 5.50 metres around 01:00 pm Tuesday 25 October and is currently at 5.28 metres and falling, with moderate flooding. The Bombala River at Bombala is expected to fall below the moderate flood level (5.00 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.

Snowy River to McKillops Bridge:

Moderate flooding is likely along the Snowy River to McKillops Bridge.

The Snowy River at McKillops Bridge is currently at 2.95 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Snowy River at McKillops Bridge is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (6.00 m) Wednesday morning.
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:

  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is for Barmah and Lower Moira. 

  • An Evacuation Warning remains current and it is too late to leave. 
  • The flood is expected to continue impacting the Barmah and Lower Moira area which means there is no longer enough time to safely leave your property.


This Emergency Warning replaces the Emergency Warning issued at 10.03am 25/10/2022.
It is now too late to leave for people in Barmah and Lower Moira community. If you have not evacuated, you should shelter in the highest location possible.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees.  
What you should do: 

If you have not already evacuated: 
  • Stay where you are and shelter in the highest location possible. 
  • Be aware that you may be isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time. 
  • Access roads out of the area are likely to be closed due to flooding.
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance. 
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.   A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.  
If you have already evacuated: 
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued. 
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • An Emergency Relief Centre has been established at the Nathalia Community Sports Centre, 42 Robertson Street, Nathalia.

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

This evacuation warning is likely to remain in place until 30/10/2022 10.00am.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Flood levels may continue to rise and spread in this area.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 26/10/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Health Messaging
  •  Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     
  • Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away  including canned and packaged foods.   
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.  
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

Returning home 
  •  Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician. For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/

Health Messaging 
  •  Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  Peoples private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away  including canned and packaged foods.   It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.

Further rainfall is forecast for the reminder of Tuesday through to Friday across parts of the Murray River Basin, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.

 
Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:

  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Albury. 
  • Moderate flooding is occurring at Corowa. Minor flooding is possible at Yarrawonga Downstream and Tocumwal.
  • The Murray River at Albury is currently at 4.39 metres and steady, with minor flooding. Subject to the change of releases from the Hume Dam, the Murray River at Albury may remain above the minor flood level (4.30 m) until Friday.
  • The Murray River at Corowa may reach around 6.25 metres around Wednesday, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Yarrawonga Downstream may reach around 6.50 metres Wednesday afternoon, with minor flooding. Further rises are possible.
  • The Murray River at Tocumwal is currently at 6.37 metres and steady, below the minor flood level (6.40 m). Renewed rises are likely later in the week and the river level may reach the minor flood level (6.40 m) during Friday.
This is an update, replacing the Advice message issued at 4.35 PM 24/10/2022
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.


Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Barham to Wentworth.

Floodwaters from the Campaspe and Goulburn Rivers combined with flows down the Murray River have caused major flooding at Echuca and Moama. River levels at Echuca Wharf have exceeded the October 1993 (94.77m AHD) and November 1975 (94.80m AHD) floods, and currently peaking slightly below 95.00m AHD, with major flooding.

Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream will be refined once the upstream flood peaks along the Murray River and its tributaries are observed.

  • The Murray River at Swan Hill is likely to exceed the minor flood level (4.50m) during Saturday and may reach the major flood level (4.70m) during the first week of November (2 to 5 November). This is similar to the October 1993 flood event.
  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction may reach around 10.70m during Thursday. The river level may reach around 11.00m during Sunday, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Boundary Bend may reach the moderate flood level (8.50m) around Friday. Further rises are possible.
  • The Murray River at Euston may reach the minor flood level (9.10m) during mid November. Further rises are possible.
  • The Murray River at Mildura Weir may reach the minor flood level (36.00m AHD) around 7 to 10 November. Further rises are possible.

  • Further rainfall is forecast for the reminder of Tuesday through to Friday across parts of the Murray River Basin, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesnt take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
Community newsletter 
A community newsletter for Swan Hill has been developed to assist with any questions locals may have. Go to: Community Newsletter - Swan Hill.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels may cause flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Some agricultural land may be vulnerable to flooding. Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Local roads may be closed.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au in New South Wales and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This Flood Advice is being issued for properties along the Pyramid Creek from Kow Swamp to Kerang.

  • Increased flows from Kow Swamp into Pyramid Creek are expected in the coming days. Flood waters may impact properties along the Pyramid Creek from Kow Swamp to Kerang.
  • This increased risk may continue for at least a week, likely through to the end of October.
  • Stay informed - be aware of local conditions and remain alert. Listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes. Conditions can change and become worse quickly.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • If you haven't already, you should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
Impacts in your area
  • Areas around the Pyramid Creek will be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers, and can damage levees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service 

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message for this incident.

Major flooding is possible along the Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge from Wednesday afternoon.

With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease.

What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing 
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens.
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.

The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
